<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-931-432  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 931 432.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 4 1989 v6 n48 p126(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Despite cost cutting, IBM fails to win Wall Street's confidences.andO;(further downsizing expected)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Wall Street analysts, still reeling from IBM's poor 3rd qtr 1989,expect IBM will introduce yet another incentive program to reducethe size of its work force.andP;  Although IBM has already reduced itspersonnel by 19,000 employees through voluntary attrition since1985 and closed six manufacturing plants, its stock prices remainlow.andP;  Analysts say the cuts are not reducing expenses enough andthat expenses are still totaling around 30 percent of revenues.andO;Some analysts think IBM may try aggressive pricing strategiesbefore proceeding with its downsizing, rumored to include a workforce reduction of 60,000 and more plant closures.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (securities).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Cost ReductionWall StreetProfitThird QuarterComputer industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Total U.S. employees; reductions in U.S. work force. (table)Closing stock price for week following earnings report. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Despite Cost Cutting, IBM Fails To Win Wall Street's ConfidenceandM;More belt-tightening is expected at IBM as that company wrestles with adisappointed Wall Street.andM;Analysts last week predicted IBM will introduce another early-retirementprogram or similar incentive designed to significantly reduce the company'shead count.andP;  Rumors of such a program have been intense on Wall Street.andM;&quot;IBM's costs are way out of line,&quot; said Peter Labe, chairman of Labe Simpsonandamp; Co., a New York brokerage.andP;  &quot;There is infinite room for cutting.&quot;andM;IBM executives have confirmed that cost-cutting measures are likely.andP;  SeniorVice President George Conrades, in Armonk, N.Y., said last month that further&quot;restructuring&quot; is expected.andP;  &quot;You will see ongoing trimming wherever wecan--in any place that is not directly involved with the customer,&quot; he said.andM;IBM officials would not comment specifically on reports of an additionalearly retirement program.andM;A voluntary-attrition program, which offers financial incentives to employeesto leave the company, was announced in October.andP;  That program, expected totrim from 600 to 1,000 employees from IBM's payroll, was the company's thirdvoluntary-attrition program in as many years.andM;Those programs have helped ax more than 19,000 U.S.andP;  employees from IBM'swork force since 1985.andP;  IBM has also closed six manufacturing plants.andM;Despite these dramatic cutbacks, Wall Street analysts have turned thumbs downon the company's stock since IBM shocked them by reporting poor results forthe third quarter ended Sept. 30.andM;Analysts had been expecting the company to earn between $2.10 and $2.30 ashare for the quarter.andP;  Instead, IBM earned $1.51 a share.andP;  Earnings weredown 30 percent from the same period last year.andM;IBM's stock has ranged from a 52-week high of $130 to a low of $96.andP;  It wastrading at $99.38 last week.andM;&quot;Wall Street has turned their back on IBM,&quot; said Labe, who stoppedrecommending the stock two months ago.andP;  &quot;It's just another cheap stockfloating out there.&quot;andM;IBM's attrition programs have failed to make a significant dent incompanywide sales and general administrative expenses.andP;  Those expenses totalabout 30 percent of revenue at IBM, while similar companies run at about 25percent, said Steven Milunovich, an analyst for First Boston Corp. of NewYork.andM;Milunovich put a hold on the stock Sept. 27 when IBM announced thatthird-quarter earnings would be disappointing.andP;  &quot;That was the straw thatbroke the camel's back,&quot; he said.andM;While Wall Street agrees that IBM must boost its bottom line, not allanalysts expect immediate staff cuts.andP;  Rick Martin, of New York brokeragePrudential-Bache Securities, expects IBM to first experiment with moreaggressive pricing to boost its growth.andP;  If that fails, Martin expects, IBMwill proceed with a massive downsizing, eliminating as many as 60,000employees and closing additional plants by 1994.andM;Either way, Martin, who recently cut his 1990 estimate from $10.30 to $9.15,recommends that clients avoid the stock.andP;  He believes things will get worsefor IBM in 1990 as revenue growth slows.andO;</TEXT></DOC>